\begin{align*}p(x) &= \frac{x^2 + x + 1}{x^2 + 1}\\p’(x) &= \frac{(2x + 1)(x^2 + 1) – (x^2 + x + 1)(2x)}{(x^2 + 1)^2}\\ &= \frac{(2x^3 + 2x + x^2 + 1) – (2x^3 + 2x^2 + x)}{(x^2 +1)^2}\\&= \frac{1 – x^2}{(x^2 + 1)^2}\end{align*}
The critical point is $x=1$, and $x=-1$. Hence, for all $x\neq1, \; p(x)$ is decreasing. Also, as $p(1)=\frac{3}{2}$ and $p(-1)=\frac{1}{2}$, the range is $\frac{1}{2}\leq p(x)\leq\frac{3}{2}$</think> <answer>$\fbox{Answer:}\quad\frac{1}{2}\leq p(x)\leq 1$</answer>

